23
00:01:30,619 --> 00:01:35,150
So the more dangerous failure
is not always an error page.

24
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:40,470
Sometimes the system returns two
hundred status code, but the results

25
00:01:40,519 --> 00:01:43,239
are empty, incomplete, or not useful.

26
00:01:43,739 --> 00:01:48,169
For the infrastructure side, the request
may look successful, but from the

27
00:01:48,169 --> 00:01:50,629
user side, the experience has failed.

28
00:01:51,110 --> 00:01:55,350
So the key here is empty does
not always means correct.

29
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,189
So we will see what can go wrong.

30
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:00,019
What can go wrong?

31
00:02:00,540 --> 00:02:04,019
In distributed search, many
failures can happen quietly.

32
00:02:04,519 --> 00:02:09,780
A traffic spike can overwhelm
shards, and some shards may return

33
00:02:09,780 --> 00:02:11,769
incomplete or degraded results.

34
00:02:12,310 --> 00:02:16,659
One slow node can delay the
entire response, and sometimes

35
00:02:16,659 --> 00:02:20,060
the system returns empty results
without raising a clear error.

36
00:02:20,689 --> 00:02:27,450
These failures are very dangerous because
they may not appear as obvious outages

37
00:02:28,349 --> 00:02:32,709
In sometimes building infrastructure
dashboards may show that the system is

38
00:02:32,709 --> 00:02:38,939
technically alive while users are still
experiencing the poor search quality.

39
00:02:39,429 --> 00:02:45,109
That is why we need to monitor not
only errors and latency, but also users

40
00:02:45,109 --> 00:02:50,889
facing signals like zero result queries,
query reformulations, and abandonment.

41
00:02:51,649 --> 00:02:56,629
I would say the real goal is not
only to prevent system failure, but

42
00:02:56,629 --> 00:03:01,070
the goal is to prevent a bad user
experience before user escalates.

43
00:03:01,750 --> 00:03:05,070
Now we will see the problems
with reactive fallback.

44
00:03:05,599 --> 00:03:10,369
So in many systems, fallback is
often only after an incident.

45
00:03:11,039 --> 00:03:15,229
A production issue happens
and a team adds a patch.

46
00:03:15,589 --> 00:03:18,279
Another issue happens and
another rule is added.

47
00:03:18,889 --> 00:03:24,259
So over the time, fallback becomes a
collection of reactive fixes instead

48
00:03:24,259 --> 00:03:26,619
of designing a reliability layer.

49
00:03:27,239 --> 00:03:33,359
But high traffic distributor systems
that we have expose new failure modes.

50
00:03:33,550 --> 00:03:36,800
They expose faster than the
reactive patches and keep up.

51
00:03:37,519 --> 00:03:42,170
But fallback should be treated as
a first-class architecture pattern.

52
00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:47,780
It should be designed from the beginning,
including capacity, routing, freshness,

53
00:03:48,220 --> 00:03:50,890
monitoring, and user experience.

54
00:03:51,460 --> 00:03:58,600
And we can leverage AI and data-driven
analysis can also help us by identifying

55
00:03:58,650 --> 00:04:03,360
a repeated zero results, traffic
anomalies, and failure patterns.

56
00:04:04,130 --> 00:04:08,520
The main point that I wanted to
emphasize here is fallback should

57
00:04:08,520 --> 00:04:11,000
be engineered, not improvised.

58
00:04:11,430 --> 00:04:17,750
Now we will see the fan-out amplification
and a hidden threat in this slide.

59
00:04:18,150 --> 00:04:21,910
Fan-out is one of the hidden
risks in distributed system.

60
00:04:22,840 --> 00:04:26,270
A single query may be sent
to multiple shards at a time.

61
00:04:26,650 --> 00:04:30,210
So this improves speed through
parallelism, but it also

62
00:04:30,210 --> 00:04:32,550
increases the failure surface.

63
00:04:33,050 --> 00:04:37,750
If most shards respond quickly,
but one shard is slow, so the whole

64
00:04:37,750 --> 00:04:39,640
query can be delayed in this case.

65
00:04:39,990 --> 00:04:44,300
That is why the tail latency
is very important here.

66
00:04:45,100 --> 00:04:47,820
Users do not experience average latency.

67
00:04:48,260 --> 00:04:51,490
They experience the specific
request they are waiting for.

68
00:04:52,370 --> 00:04:57,320
So that's gonna that will make fan-out
efficiency through Go routines.

69
00:04:57,810 --> 00:04:59,660
But concurrency must be controlled.

70
00:05:00,180 --> 00:05:05,350
So without having these limits, the same
concurrency that improves throughput

71
00:05:05,350 --> 00:05:08,080
can also increase blast radius.

72
00:05:08,570 --> 00:05:13,560
So for this one, we can have
resilient Go systems that need

73
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:18,800
context deadlines, timeout budgets,
cancellations, worker limits, and

74
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:20,870
clear rules for partial results.

75
00:05:21,300 --> 00:05:25,880
Now we will see one of the important
slide, which is the architecture overview.

76
00:05:26,470 --> 00:05:31,100
So in the architecture is basically
is built around layered resilience.

77
00:05:31,630 --> 00:05:36,280
The distributed re-retrieval layer
sends queries to primary shards.

78
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:41,470
Circuit breaker is there to monitor
system health and decide-- it

79
00:05:41,470 --> 00:05:46,270
will decide when traffic should
move away from the primary path.

80
00:05:46,960 --> 00:05:52,430
The fallback index provides like a
lightweight, it is always available for

81
00:05:52,430 --> 00:05:58,450
results, and we have bulkheads to protect
fallback capacity anyways from being

82
00:05:58,450 --> 00:06:01,330
consumed by primary system failures.

83
00:06:01,779 --> 00:06:07,450
So each layer is basically defining
a clear responsibility, and the

84
00:06:07,450 --> 00:06:10,239
retrieval hands handles the fan-outs.

85
00:06:10,680 --> 00:06:15,830
So the circuit breaker controls routing,
the fallback index supports gracefully

86
00:06:15,830 --> 00:06:19,370
degradation, bulkheads isolate resources.

87
00:06:19,669 --> 00:06:21,820
So this is the defense in depth.

88
00:06:22,410 --> 00:06:25,730
We do not depend on one
component to save the system.

89
00:06:26,160 --> 00:06:30,599
Instead, multiple layers work together
to protect the user experience.

90
00:06:31,120 --> 00:06:33,450
Now we will see the fallback index.

91
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:38,369
So a fallback index should
always-- should not just be a

92
00:06:38,369 --> 00:06:40,720
small copy of the main index.

93
00:06:41,180 --> 00:06:44,669
It should be designed specifically
for failure scenarios.

94
00:06:45,129 --> 00:06:50,139
That means it should be lightweight,
fast, predictable, and isolated

95
00:06:50,139 --> 00:06:51,440
from the primary system.

96
00:06:52,440 --> 00:06:56,979
It does not need every ranking
feature or every document.

97
00:06:57,209 --> 00:07:01,429
It needs enough high-confidence
data to keep the user when the

98
00:07:01,429 --> 00:07:03,289
primary system is degraded.

99
00:07:03,789 --> 00:07:08,419
This can include pop-popular
queries, common help articles,

100
00:07:08,889 --> 00:07:13,550
recent successful results, curated
mappings, or simplified data.

101
00:07:14,419 --> 00:07:20,739
We can leverage AI and query log analysis
that can help decide what belongs in

102
00:07:20,739 --> 00:07:27,089
fallback by identifying frequently used
content and also the most common failures.

103
00:07:27,470 --> 00:07:29,500
The goal here is not perfection.

104
00:07:30,129 --> 00:07:32,919
The goal here is to keep
the user moving forward.

105
00:07:33,419 --> 00:07:38,909
In the next slide, we will s-- we will see
about the circuit breaker-driven routing.

106
00:07:39,399 --> 00:07:43,579
So the circuit breaker helps the
system fail in a controlled way.

107
00:07:44,179 --> 00:07:48,959
In the closed state, where the traffic
flows normally to the primary index,

108
00:07:49,319 --> 00:07:56,039
the system basically monitors latencies,
errors, timeouts, and irregular quantity.

109
00:07:56,879 --> 00:08:00,849
If failures cross a
threshold, the circuit opens.

110
00:08:01,499 --> 00:08:05,169
At that point, traffic
moves to a fallback index.

111
00:08:05,709 --> 00:08:11,139
So instead of continuing to overload
the unhealthy primary system, later--

112
00:08:11,399 --> 00:08:16,919
the later happens, the circuit moves
to half-open state, where limited

113
00:08:16,919 --> 00:08:21,439
probe requests check whether the
primary system has recovered or not.

114
00:08:22,029 --> 00:08:26,239
If the probes succeed, traffic
gradually returns, and if they

115
00:08:26,239 --> 00:08:28,149
fail, the circuit opens again.

116
00:08:28,619 --> 00:08:34,179
So the key idea h-here is that
the fallback routing should be

117
00:08:34,219 --> 00:08:36,909
automatic, fast, and measurable.

118
00:08:37,099 --> 00:08:40,399
We should not wait for the
manual intervention while users

119
00:08:40,399 --> 00:08:41,919
are already seeing failure.

120
00:08:42,709 --> 00:08:47,879
In the next s-slide, we will see about
bulkhead-based res-resource isolation.

121
00:08:48,499 --> 00:08:53,309
So the bulkhead pattern that that
comes basically from ship design.

122
00:08:53,869 --> 00:08:58,279
So if one compartment floods,
the other ship should not sink.

123
00:08:58,899 --> 00:09:01,469
So the whole other ship should not sink.

124
00:09:01,469 --> 00:09:04,479
That is the main idea
behind the bulkhead pattern.

125
00:09:05,039 --> 00:09:09,509
So in software, the bulkhead
isolate failures domain so that

126
00:09:09,509 --> 00:09:11,459
the overload is in one area.

127
00:09:11,979 --> 00:09:16,319
If it is in one area, it does not
consume to all shared resources.

128
00:09:17,029 --> 00:09:22,849
In Go, this can be implemented through
separate goroutine pools, connection

129
00:09:22,849 --> 00:09:26,769
pools, and we can use semaphore
limits and context cancellations.

130
00:09:27,159 --> 00:09:32,199
This is very important for fallback
because if the primary search path

131
00:09:32,199 --> 00:09:39,129
consumes all CPU, memory, connections, or
goroutines, then the fallback cannot help.

132
00:09:39,829 --> 00:09:43,109
In-- if it exists in
design but not in reality.

133
00:09:43,769 --> 00:09:49,159
But they-- but we have bulkheads
to ensure that the fallback has

134
00:09:49,159 --> 00:09:53,589
protected capacity, so even when
the primary path is under stress.

135
00:09:53,659 --> 00:09:58,869
So the main point that I would like to
emphasize about this one is fallback

136
00:09:58,869 --> 00:10:01,429
must be isolated from the failure.

137
00:10:02,079 --> 00:10:04,149
It is desi-- it is designed to survive.

138
00:10:04,649 --> 00:10:08,529
So now we will see about
avoiding zero-result queries.

139
00:10:09,089 --> 00:10:13,179
So avoiding zero-result queries
are one of the worst search

140
00:10:13,319 --> 00:10:14,609
outcomes that I would say.

141
00:10:15,319 --> 00:10:18,629
They may return two hundred
status code, but for the user,

142
00:10:18,629 --> 00:10:20,259
they feel like complete dead-end.

143
00:10:20,839 --> 00:10:23,334
To reduce this, we need layered defense.

144
00:10:24,104 --> 00:10:29,294
First of all, the primary index should
perform full search with normal ranking.

145
00:10:29,684 --> 00:10:34,414
If that does not produce useful
results, then query relaxation can

146
00:10:34,414 --> 00:10:39,414
help by loosening strict filters,
correcting spellings, expanding

147
00:10:39,414 --> 00:10:41,234
terms, or applying synonyms.

148
00:10:41,864 --> 00:10:47,884
If a primary path is failing or still
produces poor results, the fallback index

149
00:10:47,884 --> 00:10:50,204
should provide meaningful alternatives.

150
00:10:51,124 --> 00:10:57,584
AI can help through semantic matching,
intent dis-detection, spelling correction,

151
00:10:57,944 --> 00:11:00,304
and intelligent query expansion.

152
00:11:01,114 --> 00:11:03,604
The goal is not to pretend
nothing has failed.

153
00:11:04,034 --> 00:11:09,064
The goal is to avoid giving the
user a blank result when when

154
00:11:09,064 --> 00:11:12,054
useful alternatives still exist.

155
00:11:12,264 --> 00:11:14,424
So we wanted to avoid this thing.

156
00:11:15,124 --> 00:11:20,204
The next slide we will see about
query log-driven synonym optimization.

157
00:11:20,984 --> 00:11:25,214
So search quality improves
when we learn about query logs.

158
00:11:25,854 --> 00:11:31,224
Static synonyms are always there or
like dictionaries will become outdated

159
00:11:31,474 --> 00:11:34,344
because user language keeps changing.

160
00:11:35,064 --> 00:11:39,774
Users may search with abbreviations,
misspellings, brand names, or

161
00:11:39,774 --> 00:11:44,094
even poor description that do not
exactly match indexed content.

162
00:11:44,674 --> 00:11:46,884
So the query logs reveal these gaps.

163
00:11:47,104 --> 00:11:51,854
So if a query often results a
zero results, it may need synonym

164
00:11:51,854 --> 00:11:57,014
expansion, content improvement, ranking
adjustment, or fallback support.

165
00:11:57,624 --> 00:12:01,234
So the reformulation is
always is also valuable here.

166
00:12:01,904 --> 00:12:07,094
In terms of when user searches once,
gets no results, and then changes

167
00:12:07,094 --> 00:12:09,914
the query, the second query starts.

168
00:12:10,304 --> 00:12:13,904
Then the second query, which
shows the system failed to

169
00:12:13,904 --> 00:12:15,315
understand the first time.

170
00:12:16,075 --> 00:12:21,114
So we can leverage AI by clustering
similar queries, detecting

171
00:12:21,114 --> 00:12:24,944
intent pla-- patterns, and
suggesting synonym candidates.

172
00:12:25,285 --> 00:12:29,404
But tuning must be very... We have to
do the tuning very carefully because

173
00:12:29,404 --> 00:12:32,264
broad synonyms can reduce precision.

174
00:12:32,764 --> 00:12:37,824
Next, we will see about connecting
infrastructure signals to user impact.

175
00:12:38,695 --> 00:12:43,204
So infrastructure metrics and user
metrics tell different parts of a story.

176
00:12:43,615 --> 00:12:49,204
So the infrastructure metrics are nothing
but the P ninety-nine latency, timeout

177
00:12:49,204 --> 00:12:55,504
rates, shard failures, circuit breaker
tilts, CPU memory, and a connection usage.

178
00:12:56,164 --> 00:13:01,294
But the user metrics include zero
result frequency, query reformulation

179
00:13:01,294 --> 00:13:05,614
rate, abandonment, support
escalation, and click behavior.

180
00:13:06,304 --> 00:13:07,244
Both are needed.

181
00:13:07,535 --> 00:13:12,584
A system can have good average latency
and still fails user at a tail.

182
00:13:13,485 --> 00:13:17,815
It can also return no technical
errors, but still provide poor results

183
00:13:18,674 --> 00:13:23,834
We can have AI-assisted monitoring
that can help us in connecting these

184
00:13:23,834 --> 00:13:28,774
signals by identifying patterns across
telemetry and even user behavior.

185
00:13:29,404 --> 00:13:32,654
So for search, the uptime
alone is not enough here.

186
00:13:33,364 --> 00:13:37,994
The system should not re-- only respond,
it should respond with something useful.

187
00:13:38,474 --> 00:13:39,764
That is important here.

188
00:13:40,364 --> 00:13:45,134
In the next slide, we will see about
early detection be-before user feels it.

189
00:13:45,634 --> 00:13:48,674
Support escalations
are lagging indicators.

190
00:13:48,804 --> 00:13:53,254
So by the time the user opens the
ticket, abandon sessions, and give

191
00:13:53,254 --> 00:13:59,094
negative feedback, the damage has
already happened, so we cannot do

192
00:13:59,094 --> 00:14:01,764
anything about the damage at this point.

193
00:14:02,224 --> 00:14:05,784
So a better approach is to
detect leading indicators early.

194
00:14:06,154 --> 00:14:10,984
These includes raising tail latencies
more circuit breaker trips, shard

195
00:14:10,984 --> 00:14:16,814
timeouts, higher zero result rates, and
unusual query reformulation patterns.

196
00:14:17,194 --> 00:14:22,524
So these signals show degradation before
it becomes visible as business impact.

197
00:14:23,184 --> 00:14:28,454
So when leading the indicators across
these thresholds indicators that acro--

198
00:14:28,514 --> 00:14:33,244
that cross these thresholds and also
the system that can trigger fallback

199
00:14:33,244 --> 00:14:38,614
routing, relax queries, protect
resources, and alert engineering teams.

200
00:14:39,174 --> 00:14:42,004
The u- the ideal outcome
is very simple here.

201
00:14:42,184 --> 00:14:45,284
Users should not notice the
incident before the system

202
00:14:45,284 --> 00:14:46,884
already responded safely.

203
00:14:47,654 --> 00:14:51,624
Now we will talk about one of
the important things which are

204
00:14:51,624 --> 00:14:53,444
like the key design principles.

205
00:14:54,374 --> 00:14:58,084
Let's summarize the main design
principles that we spoke about.

206
00:14:58,564 --> 00:15:01,614
The first one is fallback
must be first class.

207
00:15:02,104 --> 00:15:06,774
It should be designed from day one,
not added after the first major

208
00:15:06,774 --> 00:15:08,274
incident or something like that.

209
00:15:09,044 --> 00:15:11,934
And the second would be
design against fan-out.

210
00:15:12,264 --> 00:15:17,804
So Go makes concurrency easy, but
e-every fan-out boundaries that

211
00:15:17,804 --> 00:15:22,404
we have needs timeout budgets,
cancellations, and concurrency limits.

212
00:15:22,814 --> 00:15:26,224
So the third I would say
is use a defense in depth.

213
00:15:26,714 --> 00:15:31,395
Circuit breakers control logic, and
bulkheads protect fallback capacity.

214
00:15:32,145 --> 00:15:36,055
And fourth, I would think
of is measure user outcomes.

215
00:15:37,015 --> 00:15:40,805
Uptime is very important here when
it comes to measuring user outcomes.

216
00:15:41,265 --> 00:15:47,284
So but search quality also depends on
zero, zero result frequency, reformulation

217
00:15:47,284 --> 00:15:49,064
rate, and support escalation.

218
00:15:49,905 --> 00:15:53,735
And fifth, I would think about
is treat query logs as continuous

219
00:15:53,735 --> 00:15:56,665
feedback, and don't take it lightly.

220
00:15:56,665 --> 00:16:00,585
So they reveal the vocabulary
gaps, synonym opportunities,

221
00:16:00,585 --> 00:16:01,715
and silent failures.

222
00:16:02,314 --> 00:16:05,165
And finally, use UI practically.

223
00:16:05,655 --> 00:16:11,075
AI should improve ca- Query understanding,
anomaly detection, sy- synonym

224
00:16:11,075 --> 00:16:13,055
discovery, and fallback decisions.

225
00:16:13,405 --> 00:16:15,625
Not just being added just as a buzzword.

226
00:16:16,125 --> 00:16:19,155
Thank you so much for
giving me this opportunity.

227
00:16:19,425 --> 00:16:24,455
And to close on resilient self-search,
this is all about giving users a

228
00:16:24,455 --> 00:16:29,435
useful path forward even when parts
of the systems are under stress.

229
00:16:29,765 --> 00:16:34,755
So failures are, like, normal in
distributed system world, but what

230
00:16:34,755 --> 00:16:40,935
matters is whether we design the system
